Fig. 1
a–c show the typical TEM images of BC-31, BC-61 and BC-101 with average diameter of ∼3.7, ∼5, and ∼6 nm, respectively which clearly reveals the overall diameter (d) increases (Table 1
) with reaction time (Fig. 1d) indicating a nucleation and growth of B-CNPs [36]. AFM images (Fig. S2a-e and S2b-f) of BC-31, BC-61 and BC-101 on Si substrate show height (h) of 1.6, 3.5 and 5–6 nm, which suggests the sphericity of B-CNPs increases with size.

Here, we label the HeLa cells with our B-CNPs. For cell labeling, HeLa cells are cultured in MEM medium containing 30 μl B-CNPs and incubated for 5 h. As shown in Fig. 5
                     a, HeLa cells, which are incubated without B-CNPs were colorless. However, HeLa cells with BC-101 show stronger fluorescence when compared to BC-61 and BC-31 (Fig. 5b–d), which was expected as the QY is high for BC-101. In addition, B-CNPs is used for yeast cells labeling as well (Fig. 6
                     ). For yeast cell labeling, the cells are grown in YPD medium for 12 h and cells are collected and re-suspended in 1 M Phosphate Buffered saline (pH – 7.5) along with 30 μl of B-CNPs for 24 h. The cell imaging results suggest that our B-CNPs (BC-31, BC-61 and BC-101) can be used in biomedical and clinical analysis. Furthermore, the experimental results clearly suggest that bio-compatible materials with a QY as low as 0.5% can be used for cell imaging.
